Anonymous Sun 28 Jan 2024 22:19:03 No.62915910 Report
Quoted By: >>62915941
>>62915664
Most mammals have extremely poor colour vision, probably as a result of our ancestors being small nocturnal ratlike creatures during the dinosaurian eras, as colour vision wasn't necessary in poor light conditions. Fur can only produce a handful of colours, generally whites browns and blacks, probably because our ancestors couldn't see anything more than that, and green camouflage doesn't really help in the dark. Even though many mammals are now diurnal, they still generally have really bad colour vision. Only exception is the apes, which is also where you see the only really brightly coloured mammals (blue mandrill faces, red baboon asses), but fur still can't make any more complex pigments than that. Sloths sometimes have green fur, but that's because of symbiotic algae growth and not true fur pigmentation.
